ci: use trusted publishing for PyPI

use gcc on osx

This seems to help with some compilation issues.

docs: move fork information to history

Most users are not interested in this info now.

Enabled feature parity with htmltidy C frontend (#105)

In the official HTMLTidy C Frontend code, there will always be a CleanAndRepair step after parsing as long as there is no catastrophic failure (catastrohpic failure is statuscode < 0). In this library, it's only done when parseString or parseFile returned a status code > 0.

The official source code does it on status >= 0 as one can see here: https://github.com/htacg/tidy-html5/blob/d08ddc2860aa95ba8e301343a30837f157977cba/console/tidy.c#L2516

This became obvious when we compared the output of tidy (official frontend) with the output of this library on a bulk HTML tidying; the approval tests (that test for exact same output) showed a large number of diffs that vanished as soon as we fixed this.

Also, there is a small error: char-encoding is not a valid Python kwarg; it has to be char_encoding.

Co-authored-by: Jonas Dedden <jonas.dedden@deepl.com>
Co-authored-by: Michal Čihař <michal@cihar.com>

Enabled feature parity with htmltidy C frontend (#105)

In the official HTMLTidy C Frontend code, there will always be a CleanAndRepair step after parsing as long as there is no catastrophic failure (catastrohpic failure is statuscode < 0). In this library, it's only done when parseString or parseFile returned a status code > 0.

The official source code does it on status >= 0 as one can see here: https://github.com/htacg/tidy-html5/blob/d08ddc2860aa95ba8e301343a30837f157977cba/console/tidy.c#L2516

This became obvious when we compared the output of tidy (official frontend) with the output of this library on a bulk HTML tidying; the approval tests (that test for exact same output) showed a large number of diffs that vanished as soon as we fixed this.

Also, there is a small error: char-encoding is not a valid Python kwarg; it has to be char_encoding.
